Moran’s I statistic is a test of spatial correlation, which will result in the form of analysis: global spatial autocorrelation presented as a Moran scatter plot. Moran’s I quantifies spatial autocorrelation, with values ranging from − 1 (indicating perfect negative autocorrelation) to + 1 (indicating perfect positive autocorrelation), and values near 0 suggesting a random spatial pattern. Statistical significance was determined using z-scores and p-values, with p < 0.05 considered statistically significant positive or negative spatial autocorrelation (Equation: Xi = variable of interest at the particular location, Xj = variable of interest at another location, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
